When you type “get me JMS queues”, it works like this technically:
Frontend sends prompt
In [AppChatbot.jsx (line 267)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/frontend/src/components/AppChatbot.jsx:267), sendPrompt() sends a POST request to:
POST /chatbot/query
Body contains:
{
  "prompt": "get me jms queues",
  "token": "...tenant bearer token from localStorage...",
  "baseUrl": "...tenant baseUrl from localStorage...",
  "packages": [...]
}
Backend receives request
In [server.js (line 3354)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/server.js:3354), route:
app.post("/chatbot/query", async (req, res) => { ... })
It cleans baseUrl, then calls:
handleChatbotPrompt({ prompt, token, baseUrl, packages })
Tenant context is built
Inside [server.js (line 3248)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/server.js:3248), handleChatbotPrompt() calls:
createChatbotTenantContext({ token, baseUrl, packages })
That creates:
{
  token,
  baseUrl,
  tenantId,
  packages,
  hasTenantConnection
}
AI/MCP path is used
If OPENAI_API_KEY or AI_INTENT_API_KEY exists, backend calls:
runMcpChat({ prompt, tenantContext })
This is in [mcpClient.js (line 64)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/mcp/mcpClient.js:64).
Tool list is sent to OpenRouter
runMcpChat() builds messages and tools:
const tools = getMcpToolsForOpenRouter();
The tool definition for JMS queues is in [toolRegistry.js (line 474)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/mcp/toolRegistry.js:474):
name: "list_jms_queues"
description: "List JMS queues in the tenant..."
So OpenRouter sees that get me jms queues matches the tool list_jms_queues.
AI chooses the tool
OpenRouter returns something like:
{
  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "function": {
        "name": "list_jms_queues",
        "arguments": "{}"
      }
    }
  ]
}
Then runMcpChat() extracts:
const toolName = toolCall.function?.name;
const toolParams = parseToolArguments(toolCall);
Backend executes the real tool
Still in [mcpClient.js (line 111)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/mcp/mcpClient.js:111), it calls:
executeMcpTool(toolName, toolParams, tenantContext)
That reaches the handler in [toolHandlers.js (line 777)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/mcp/toolHandlers.js:777):
list_jms_queues: async (params, tenantContext) => { ... }
JMS handler checks tenant connection
It first calls:
requireTenantConnection(tenantContext)
If token/baseUrl is missing, it returns:
Connect a tenant first...
If connected, it continues.
Actual SAP API call happens
list_jms_queues calls:
getJmsQueueRecords(tenantContext.baseUrl, tenantContext.token)
That function is in [server.js (line 1852)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/server.js:1852).
It builds possible tenant base URLs using:
buildBaseUrlCandidates(baseUrl)
Then calls SAP:
GET {candidate}/api/v1/Queues?$format=json&$top=500
Authorization: Bearer <token>
SAP response is normalized
   getJmsQueueRecords() passes the SAP response through:
unwrapODataResults(response.data)
mapQueueRecord(...)
mapQueueRecord() is in [server.js (line 939)](C:/Users/yashwanth.gr/Desktop/Tenant-Access/backend/server.js:939). It converts SAP fields into app fields like:
{
  id,
  key,
  name,
  accessType,
  usage,
  state,
  entries
}
Then queues are sorted and duplicate queue names are removed.
Tool returns result
   Back in list_jms_queues, it returns:
{
  items: filtered.map(queue => ({ type: "jms-queue", ...queue })),
  rawData: {
    total: queues.length,
    returned: filtered.length,
    healthFilter: "all"
  }
}
If you asked “failed JMS queues” or “DLQ queues”, it uses:
filterProblemJmsQueues(queues)
Summary message is generated
   runMcpChat() then calls:
summarizeToolResult({ prompt, toolName, rawData })
That creates the sentence like:
Found 12 JMS queue(s).
Frontend displays it
   Backend responds to /chatbot/query with:
{
  "message": "...",
  "items": [...queues...],
  "actions": [],
  "debug": {
    "tool": "list_jms_queues",
    "model": "...",
    "params": {}
  }
}
Frontend receives this and adds a bot message with queue items.
Short function chain
AppChatbot.sendPrompt()
  -> POST /chatbot/query
    -> handleChatbotPrompt()
      -> createChatbotTenantContext()
      -> runMcpChat()
        -> getMcpToolsForOpenRouter()
        -> callOpenRouterWithTools()
        -> parseToolArguments()
        -> executeMcpTool("list_jms_queues")
          -> TOOL_HANDLERS.list_jms_queues()
            -> requireTenantConnection()
            -> getJmsQueueRecords()
              -> buildBaseUrlCandidates()
              -> axios.get("/api/v1/Queues")
              -> unwrapODataResults()
              -> mapQueueRecord()
        -> summarizeToolResult()
    -> frontend renders message/items
There is also a fallback path if AI/MCP fails: handleChatbotPrompt() falls back to classifyChatbotIntent(), analyzePromptWithAi(), mergeIntentFallback(), and then executeTenantChatTool(). For JMS queues, that fallback still eventually calls getJmsQueueRecords().